text: Discovery of Frenolicin B as Potential Agrochemical Fungicide for Controlling Fusarium Head Blight on Wheat Chuanyu Han, Zhonghua Ma, Ziyue Wen, Chongxi Liu,* and Wensheng Xiang*

ABSTRACT: In this study, the supernatant extract from fermentation broth of Streptomyces sp. NEAU-H3 showed strong antifungal activity against Fusarium graminearum strain PH-1 in vitro and in vivo. Three known pyranonaphthoquinones were isolated by means of an activity-guided method, and frenolicin B was characterized as the main active ingredient. Frenolicin B displayed strong antifungal activity against F. graminearum strain PH-1 with an EC50 value of 0.51 mg/L, which is lower than that of carbendazim (0.78 mg/L) but higher than that of phenamacril (0.18 mg/L). Frenolicin B could also strongly inhibit the mycelial growth of Fusarium species, including F. graminearum and F. asiaticum, as well as carbendazim-resistant Fusarium strains isolated from ﬁeld, with EC50 values of 0.25−0.92 mg/L. Results from ﬁeld experiments showed that the eﬃcacy of frenolicin B in controlling Fusarium head blight at a treatment concentration of 75 g ai/ha was better than those of phenamacril (375 g ai/ha) and carbendazim (600 g ai/ha) or had no signiﬁcant diﬀerence with that of phenamacril (375 g ai/ha) in 2 years. Scanning electron microscope and transmission electron microscope observations revealed that after treating F. graminearum mycelia with frenolicin B, the mycelia appeared aberrant and had an uneven thickness and swelling, the cytoplasm had disintegrated, and some cell contents were lost. Transcriptome analysis suggests that frenolicin B might inhibit the metabolism of nucleotides and energy by aﬀecting genes involved in phosphorus utilization but did not aﬀect the expression of myosin 5, which is the speciﬁc target of phenamacril. These ﬁndings indicate that frenolicin B may be a potential agrochemical fungicide for controlling Fusarium head blight. KEYWORDS: frenolicin B, Fusarium head blight, Fusarium graminearum, antifungal activity, transcriptome

Fusarium head blight (FHB) caused by Fusarium species is a destructive disease on wheat throughout the world.1 The major species responsible for FHB are Fusarium graminearum, Fusarium asiaticum, and Fusarium culmorum.2 FHB not only results in 10−40% yield losses3 but also reduces grain quality because of the presence of mycotoxins such as deoxynivalenol and zearalenone that pose a threat to human and animal health.4,5 In China, wheat is the second staple crop after rice and has a very important role in the national food production. FHB was ﬁrst reported in 1936. Since then, the disease has become widespread in the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River and Huaihe River valleys and the eastern coastal region. In recent decades, FHB has gradually spread to the north and west wheat-growing areas of China.6 Due to the limit of cultivars with eﬀective resistance to this disease, application of chemical fungicides remains the main the strategy for controlling FHB. Since the early 1970s, benzimidazole fungicide carbendazim has been widely used to control FHB in China.3 However, continuous application with high doses of carbendazim has caused a widespread high level of resistance in the ﬁeld.7 As a result, the control eﬃcacy of carbendazim against Fusarium species decreased dramatically after 1998.8 In recent years, the novel fungicide phenamacril with speciﬁc activity against Fusarium spp. has been marketed for the management of FHB. This fungicide exhibits an excellent eﬃcacy in controlling FHB in ﬁeld trials.9 However, indoor Cite This: J. Agric. resistance risk assessment showed that mutants resistant to phenamacril were easily obtained under the selection pressure of the fungicide.3 Thus, there is an urgent demand to develop new fungicides with diﬀerent modes of action as alternatives. Actinobacteria is known to produce a vast diversity of antimicrobials including blasticidin S, kasugamycin, mildiomy- cin, validamycin, and so on, which have been widely used in agriculture as fungicides.10 During our continuous eﬀort to discover antifungal compounds with novel chemical structures or modes of action against F. graminearum, a potential antagonist, Streptomyces sp. NEAU-H3, was isolated from the rhizosphere soil of wheat, and the ethyl acetate extract derived from a ferment supernatant was tested for antifungal activity against F. graminearum. The main active component was subsequently isolated and identiﬁed as frenolicin B. Frenolicin B, a member of the pyranonaphthoquinone family, has been reported to possess a variety of biological activities, including anticancer activity,11 antimalarial activity,12 anticoccidial activity,13 and antimycoplasma activity.14 The antifungal activity in vitro against yeast and mold, such as Candida albicans, Received: Revised: November 27, 2020 Accepted: February 5, 2021 Published: February 15, 2021 *sı Supporting Information https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jafc.0c04277 J. Saccharomyces cerevisiae, Microsporum gypseum, Penicillium chrysogenum, Trichopyton interdigitale, Trichopyton mentagro- phytes, Piricularia oryzae, Asperillus fumigatus, and Asperillus niger, was disclosed by a patent.15 However, no previous study has investigated the antifungal activity of frenolicin B against Fusarium spp. Therefore, it is imperative to study its antifungal activity and the corresponding mechanisms of action to make it pa otential alternative fungicide for controlling FHB. In this paper, the in vitro antifungal activity of frenolicin B against Fusarium spp. was examined and the eﬃcacy in controlling FHB on wheat was assessed in ﬁeld trials. Furthermore, a preliminary mechanism against F. graminearum was also investigated. Microorganisms and Chemicals. Fusarium graminearum strain PH-1, originally isolated from corn in Michigan, was deposited in the Fungal Genetics Stock Center (Kansas City, MO, USA) under accession number NRRL 31084. The Fusarium strains 1−50 and 51− 100 of FHB were kindly provided by the College of Plant Protection, Nanjing Agricultural University (Nanjing, China), which were isolated from wheat collected from Yancheng and Huaian (China), respectively. All 101 Fusarium strains were maintained on potato dextrose agar (PDA) medium in the dark at 25 °C. Wheat seed (Longmai 33) was kindly provided by the Crop Resources Institute of Heilongjiang Academy of Agricultural Sciences (Harbin, China).

Carbendazim 99% technical material (TC) was purchased from Aladdin Biochemical Technology, Inc. (Shanghai, China). Carbenda- zim 80% ai wettable powder (WP) was purchased from Meifeng Agricultural Chemical Co., Ltd. (Wenzhou, China). Phenamacril 25% suspension concentrate (SC) was purchased from Jiangsu Pesticide Research Institute, Inc. (Nanjing, China). Ethyl acetate, methanol, and acetonitrile were purchased from Yunnan Xinlanjing Chemical Industry Co., Ltd. (Yuxi, China). Isolation and Identiﬁcation of Strain NEAU-H3. Antagonistic strain NEAU-H3 was isolated from the rhizosphere soil of wheat ( Triticum aestivum L.) collected from Zhumadian, Henan Province, Central China (32°98′ N, 114°02′ E). The processing of the rhizosphere soil sample and the isolation of the actinobacterial strain were performed as previously described.16 After 28 days of aerobic incubation at 28 °C, colonies were transferred and puriﬁed on the International Streptomyces Project medium 3 (ISP3)17 and maintained as glycerol suspensions (20%, v/v) at −80 °C. The genomic DNA of strain NEAU-H3 was extracted, and PCR ampliﬁcation of the 16S rRNA gene sequence was performed as previously described.18 A phylogenetic tree was constructed with a neighbor-joining algorithm19 with Kimura’s two-parameter model20 using Molecular Evolutionary Genetics Analysis (MEGA) software version 7.0.21 The stability of the topology of the phylogenetic tree was assessed using the bootstrap method with 1000 repetitions.22 The 16S rRNA gene sequence similarities between strains was calculated on the basis of pairwise alignment using the EzBioCloud server.23 The 16S rRNA gene sequence of strain NEAU-H3 was deposited in the GenBank database under accession number MN729489.

Activity Evaluation of Fermentation Extracts of NEAU-H3 against F. graminearum In Vitro. The strain NEAU-H3 was cultured on ISP 3 agar plates for 3 days at 28 °C. Then, it was inoculated into 250 mL baﬄed Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 50 mL of tryptone soy broth (TSB) and cultivated for 2 days at 28 °C with shaking at 250 rpm. After that, aliquots (2.5 mL) of the culture were transferred into 250 mL baﬄed Erlenmeyer ﬂasks ﬁlled with 50 mL of the production medium (lactose 4.0%, maltodextrin 4.0%, MOPS 2.0%, yeast extract 0.5%, pH 7.2−7.4) and cultured at 28 °C for 7 days with shaking at 250 rpm. A total of 50 mL of fermentation broth was centrifuged (4000 rpm, 20 min) to obtain a supernatant and mycelia. The supernatant was extracted with ethyl acetate (50 mL × 3), while the mycelia were extracted with methanol (50 mL × 3). After that, the extracts were evaporated in vacuo to dry and redissolved in methanol (1 mL), respectively. The antifungal activity was evaluated using the ﬁlter paper method.24 A 5 mm mycelial plug of F. graminearum strain PH-1 was transferred from the edge of the actively growing culture onto the center of PDA plates. Each ﬁlter paper (5 mm in diameter) impregnated with 10 μL of the crude extract of the supernatant or mycelia was placed on the inoculated agar between the plate margin and fungal plug. The antifungal activity was evaluated when the inoculated plates were cultured at 25 °C for 3 days.

Eﬃcacy of Supernatant Extract in Controlling FHB in Growth Chamber. Spring wheat cultivar (Longmai 33, susceptible to FHB) was used in the growth chamber test. At 5% anthesis, wheat heads with 10 cm stems were collected from the ﬁeld. A single wheat head was set in a test tube ﬁlled with sterile water. The supernatant extract concentrate dissolved in methanol was diluted in water with 0.05% Tween 20 to reach the same volume as the original supernatant. Carbendazim WP (80%, 750 mg ai/L) and phenamacril SC (25%, 750 mg ai/L) were used as positive controls, and sterile water with 0.05% Tween 20 served as a negative control. Two inoculation methods were used in the test. (1) Spray-inoculated method:25 wheat spikes were sprayed with diluted supernatant extract, 80% carbendazim WP, 25% phenamacril SC, and sterile water until numerous droplets were deposited onto the wheat heads. After droplets on wheat heads air-dried for 24 h in a growth chamber, each treated wheat head was sprayed with a 1 mL conidial suspension (104 conidia mL−1) of F. graminearum strain PH-1 containing 0.05% Tween 20. (2) Point-inoculated method:26 a 10 μL mixture of treatments and a conidial suspension of F. graminearum strain PH-1 was injected into a ﬂoret at the central section spikelet of single ﬂowering wheat heads. A total of 20 wheat heads were used for each treatment, and the experiment was conducted three times independently. The wheat heads were kept at 25 °C and 100% humidity for 3 days, and then incubation was continued at 20 °C for 7 days. For method 1, the disease severity was rated using a ﬁve-class scale, corresponding to a percentage of wheat head surface showing FHB symptoms (0, 0%; 1, 1−25%; 2, 26−50%; 3, 51−75%; 4, >75%), and the disease index (

ﬁve-class scale, corresponding to a percentage of wheat head surface showing FHB symptoms (0, 0%; 1, 1−25%; 2, 26−50%; 3, 51−75%; 4, >75%), and the disease index (DI) of each plot was calculated using the formula [(∑ number of wheat heads in each class × each evaluation class)/ (total number of wheat heads × 4)] × 100. For method 2, the DI was assessed according to the percentage of infected spikelets. The control eﬃciency was calculated using the formula: [(DI of the negative control − DI of the treatment)/(DI of the negative control)] × 100%.

Isolation and Characterization of the Antifungal Com- pounds. The antifungal compounds were isolated from the ethyl acetate extract using an in vitro antifungal activity-guided method. The fermentation broth (25 L) was centrifuged (4000 rpm, 20 min), and the supernatant was extracted with ethyl acetate three times. The ethyl acetate extract was subsequently evaporated in vacuo to aﬀord 10.0 g of oily crude extract. The crude extract was subjected to a silica gel column (100−200 mesh, Qingdao Marine Chemical Inc., China) using a successive elution of petroleum ether/ethyl acetate (1/0, 10/1, 5/1, 3/ 1, 1/1, and 1/0 v/v) to yield fractions 1−8. Fraction 6 was subjected to a Sephadex LH-20 column (25−100 μm, Pharmacia Biotech Ltd., Sweden) elution with methanol to collect three fractions (F6A, F6B, and F6C). F6B was subjected to semipreparative HPLC (YMC- Hydrosphere C18 column, 250 mm × 10 mm i.d., 5 μm, CH3CN/H2O 57/43 v/v, 3 mL/min) to give compounds 1 (tR = 11.6 min, 20.0 mg), 2 (tR = 15.0 min, 20.5 mg), and 3 (tR = 20.4 min, 80.0 mg). The structures of compounds 1−3 were determined using spectroscopic analysis. NMR spectra were measured with a Bruker Avance III-400 spectrometer in CDCl3 using TMS as an internal standard. ESI-MS data were obtained using an Agilent G6230 Q-TOF mass instrument.

Activity Evaluation of Compound 3 against Fusarium spp. In Vitro. An antifungal activity bioassay was performed against F. graminearum strain PH-1 and 100 Fusarium spp. Compound 3 dissolved in methanol was diluted with water to diﬀerent concen- trations, and these solutions were then added to PDA media. The fungus plug (5 mm in diameter) of mycelial inocula cut from the edge of actively growing colonies of each fungus was placed in the center of the agar plate and incubated at 25 °C. Carbendazim and phenamacril at diﬀerent concentrations were used as positive controls, and a sterile https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jafc.0c04277 J. Agric. Food Chem. 2021, 69, 2108−2117 Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry Figure 1. Antifungal activity of fermentation extracts of strain NEAU-H3 against F. graminearum PH-1 in vitro and in vivo: (A) antifungal activity of fermentation extracts of strain NEAU-H3 against F. graminearum in vitro, where 1 indicates the supernatant extract and 2 the mycelium extract; (B) antifungal activity of the supernatant extract of strain NEAU-H3 against F. graminearum in vivo. water plate was used as a negative control. Experiments were replicated three times. When the negative control plate was covered by more than two-thirds of a fungal mass, the percentage of inhibition was calculated with the formula inhibition (%) = (1 − mean colony diameter of the treatment/mean colony diameter of the negative control) × 100. Data were subjected to linear regression analysis, and the eﬀective concentrations required for 50% inhibition (EC50) were calculated.

Sequencing and Phylogenetic Analysis of Fusarium spp. Genomic DNA was extracted from lyophilized mycelia as previously described.27 Two DNA regions including the translation elongation factor 1-alpha (TEF1-α) and RNA polymerase II largest subunit (RPB2) genes were ampliﬁed using primer sets of EF1/EF2 and 7cf/ 11ar, respectively.28 Homology searches were carried out using the Fusarium MLST database (http://www.cbs.knaw.nl/fusarium). The sequences of each locus were aligned using MEGA 7.0 software29 and trimmed manually at the same position before being used for further analysis. Phylogenetic trees were constructed with a maximum likelihood algorithm30 using MEGA 7.0 on the basis of the combined two-locus data set. The stability of the topology of the phylogenetic tree was assessed using the bootstrap method with 1000 repetitions.22 A distance matrix was generated using Kimura’s two-parameter model.20 All positions containing gaps and missing data were eliminated from the data set (complete deletion option). The TEF1-α and RPB2 gene sequences were deposited in GenBank with accession numbers MT113018−MT113027 and MT113028−MT113037, respectively.

Eﬃcacy of Compound 3 in Controlling FHB in Field Trials. the experimental ﬁeld of Field experiments were conducted at Northeast Agricultural University (NEAU) (Heilongjiang, China) and the Plant Protection Experimental Station of Haian (PPESH) (Jiangsu, China) during summer 2018 and spring 2019 with spring wheat cultivar (Longmai 33, susceptible to FHB) and winter wheat cultivar (Zhenmai 12, moderate resistance to FHB), respectively. The cultivars were planted following normal agronomic practices. Appropriate fertilizers and herbicides were applied according to standard management practices. Four treatments for NEAU were compound 3 with 0.05% Tween 20 (75 g ai/ha), 80% carbendazim WP (600 g ai/ha), 25% phenamacril SC (375 g ai/ha), and 0.05% Tween 20 (negative control). Four treatments for PPESH were compound 3 with 0.05% Tween 20 (75 g ai/ha), compound 3 with 0.05% Tween 20 (375 g ai/ha), 25% phenamacril SC (375 g ai/ha), and 0.05% Tween 20 (negative control). The ﬁeld trials were conducted using a randomized plot design, with three replicates of each treatment, and each plot was 2 × 3 m2 in size. At 5% anthesis, each plot was sprayed with diﬀerent treatments, respectively. After 48 h, each plot was sprayed with a conidial suspension (104 conidia mL−1) of F. graminearum strain PH-1 amended with 0.05% Tween 20. Twenty-one days after inoculation, the disease severity in each plot was rated using a ﬁve=class scale, and the disease index and control eﬃciency were calculated as described above.

Eﬀect of Compound 3 on Hyphal Morphology of F. graminearum Strain PH-1. A mycelial plug (5 mm in diameter) of F. graminearum strain PH-1 cut from the periphery of a 3 day old colony was placed on the center of a PDA plate amended with compound 3 at the EC50 value. A PDA plate without compound 3 treatment was used as a control. After 3 days at 25 °C, the collected fungal masses were treated as described by Jin et al.31 and examined under a scanning electron microscope (SEM) (Hitachi SU8010, Hitachi Co., Tokyo, Japan). A mycelial plug (5 mm in diameter) of F. graminearum strain PH-1 cut from the periphery of a 3 day old colony was inoculated into 250 mL baﬄed Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 50 mL of sterilized PDB broth and cultivated at 25 °C with shaking at 180 rpm for 36 h. After that, compound 3 with a ﬁnal concentration of 0.51 mg/L was added to the broth, and the same volume of methanol was set as a control. After incubation for 6 h, the mycelia were collected by centrifugation (4000 rpm, 10 min) and treated as described by Cao et al.32 The mycelial morphology was observed under a transmission electron microscope (TEM) (Hitachi H-7650, Hitachi Co., Tokyo, Japan).

Transcriptome Assay. F. graminearum strain PH-1 was cultured in PDB as a control or with 0.51 mg/L of compound 3 as described above. At 42 h, the mycelia were collected and frozen in liquid nitrogen more than 1 h. Three replicates for each treatment were performed. The total RNA was extracted using the TRIzol Reagent (Invitrogen, CA, USA) following the instruction manual. The RNA concentration and purity were measured by a NanoDrop 2000 spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher, USA) and Labchip GX Touch HT Nucleic Acid Analyzer (PerkinElmer, USA). RNA sequencing libraries were generated using for Illumina following the the KAPA Stranded RNA-Seq Kit manufacturer’s recommendations. Then sequencing was performed on an Illumina Novaseq 6000 instrument to obtain raw data. Reference genome and gene model annotation ﬁles were downloaded from the genome Web site directly. Paired-end clean reads were aligned to the reference genome using Hisat2. FeatureCounts v1.5.0 was used to count the numbers of reads mapped to each gene.33 Then, he FPKM of each gene was calculated on the basis of the length of the gene and read counts mapped to this gene.34 Diﬀerential expression analysis was performed using the DESeq R package (1.10.1).35 The resulting P values were adjusted using Benjamini and Hochberg’s approach for controlling the false discovery rate.36 Genes with an adjusted P value <0.05 found by DESeq were assigned as diﬀerentially expressed. The R package (ClusterProﬁler/enrichplot) was employed to perform the enrichment analysis of the Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) and gene ontology (GO) by the Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) method as described previously.37,38 The parameters used in the preranked GSEA were the classic enrichment statistics, with 1000 gene set permutations, and a false discovery rate (FDR) <0.25 was recognized as statistically signiﬁcant. The transcriptome data sets were submitted to NCBI under accession number GSE147731.

Antifungal activity and structures of compounds 1−3: (A) antifungal activity of compounds 1−3 against F. graminearum PH-1; (B) structures of compounds 1−3. Quantitative RT-PCR Analysis. The RNA used for quantitative reverse transcription PCR (qRT-PCR) analysis was extracted as described above. cDNAs were constructed from 1 μg of total RNA by reverse transcription using the superscript III ﬁrst-strand synthesis system (Invitrogen, California, USA) following the manufacturer’s instructions. The qRT-PCR experiments were implemented on a QuantStudio 5 instrument (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA, USA) using PowerUp SYBR Green Master Mix (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA, USA). The running conditions were performed as described by Zhang et al.39 TEF1-α (FGSG_08811) was used as an internal control to normalize the expression data.40 The qRT-PCR experiment was repeated three times, with each sample having three replicates. The relative expression level of the genes was calculated using the 2−ΔΔCT method,41 and the standard deviation was calculated from the three biological replicates. The primers used for amplifying the TEF1-α and target genes (FGSG_04504, FGSG_07375, and FGSG_03172) are given in Table S1.

Isolation and Identiﬁcation of Strain NEAU-H3. In order to search for antifungal compounds against FHB, strain NEAU- H3 was isolated from the rhizosphere soil of wheat. The morphology of the strain NEAU-H3 on ISP3 medium is typical of Streptomyces with a white color of the mycelia. A 16S rRNA gene sequence analysis showed that strain NEAU-H3 was aﬃliated with the genus Streptomyces and shared the highest gene sequence similarity to Streptomyces xylanilyticus SR2-123T (98.76%). A phylogenetic tree based on 16S rRNA gene sequences showed that the strain formed a stable clade with S. xylanilyticus SR2-123T, which was supported by a bootstrap value of 97% in the neighbor-joining tree (Figure S1). On the basis of 16S rRNA gene sequence similarity and phylogenetic analysis, he strain NEAU-H3 was identiﬁed as a strain of Streptomyces and deposited in the China Center for Type Culture Collection (accession number CCTCC AA2018043). Activity Evaluation of Fermentation Extracts of NEAU- H3 against F. graminearum In Vitro and In Vivo. The supernatant extract, but not the mycelium extract, of strain NEAU-H3 showed strong inhibition activity against F. graminearum in vitro (Figure 1A). To determine whether the supernatant extract inhibited the growth of F. graminearum in planta, we conducted in vivo experiments by two inoculatin methods under the growth chamber conditions. In the spray- inoculated method, the control eﬃcacy of the supernatant extract was 58.67% against FHB, which was signiﬁcantly higher than those obtained from phenamacril and carbendazim. In the point-inoculated method, the control eﬃcacy of the supernatant extract exhibited no signiﬁcant diﬀerence from that of phenamacril but was obviously higher than that of carbendazim (Figure 1B). These results indicate that the supernatant extract

of strain NEAU-H3 is eﬀective against FHB under laboratory conditions. Structure Elucidation of the Antifungal Compounds. An antifungal activity-guided separation of the components inthe supernatant extract of strain NEAU-H3, using an in vitro antifungal assay, led to the isolation of three compounds as its active principles, out of which, compound 3 was the main active ingredient (Figure 2A).

Identiﬁcation of Fusarium Strains. Ten Fusarium strains, including ﬁve carbendazim-resistant strains (4, 14, 36, 78, and 98) and ﬁve carbendazim-sensitive strains (7, 17, 19, 22, and 27) (Table 1), were selected for identiﬁcation by phylogenetic analysis on the basis of the concatenated sequences of TEF1-α and RPB2. A sequence analysis revealed that the 10 strains consist of two species, F. asiaticum and F. graminearum. Strain 7 showed 99.9% sequence similarity to F. graminearum and formed a separate clade with this species in the phylogenetic tree, leading it to be identiﬁed as F. graminearum, while the sequences of the other nine strains exhibited 99.6−100.0% similarities to F. asiaticum and clustered with this species in the phylogenetic tree, resulting in their identiﬁcation as F. asiaticum https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jafc.0c04277 J. This result indicates that frenolicin B can strongly inhibit mycelium growth of both F. graminearum and F. asiaticum, which are the dominant species associated with FHB in China.2 Eﬃcacy of Frenolicin B in Controlling FHB in Field Trials. In 2018, the control eﬃcacy of treatment of frenolicin B at 75 g ai/ha was 52.94%, which was signiﬁcantly higher than those of phenamacril (375 g ai/ha) and carbendazim (600 g ai/ ha) treatments. In 2019, the control eﬃcacy of frenolicin B applied at 75 and 375 g ai/ha had no signiﬁcant diﬀerence from that of phenamacril (375 g ai/ha). Furthermore, the incidence frenolicin B treatment with two rates of FHB under concentrations were lower than those of carbendazim and phenamacril treatments in 2 years (Table 2). Thus, these results imply that frenolicin B should be a good candidate for controlling FHB in the ﬁeld. Eﬀect of Frenolicin B on Micromorphology and Ultrastructure of F. graminearum Mycelia. SEM and TEM analyses further illustrated the micromorphology and ultrastructural alterations of mycelia that resulted from treat- ment with frenolicin B at 0.51 mg/L (the EC50 value), under which the mycelia have viability. Mycelia incubated without frenolicin B showed equal widths, even surfaces, and symmetri- cally distributed branching (Figure 4A) and had normal plasma membranes, organized cytoplasm, and visible nuclei and septum with well-deﬁned envelopes (Figure 4B−D). However, the frenolicin B caused morphological and ultrastructure changes in mycelia which had suﬀered severe damage. As shown in Figure 4E, a disorganized hyphal growth pattern and uneven thickness, swelling, and distortion hyphae were observed in frenolicin B

frenolicin B phenamacril carbendazim control frenolicin B frenolicin B phenamacril control treated F. graminearum. Moreover, on the basis of a TEM analysis, the cytoplasm appeared aggregated and not evenly distributed (Figure 4F), some cell contents were lost and even developed a cavity (Figure 4G), and the septate disappeared (Figure 4H). Transcriptome Assay. To further investigate the under- lying molecular mechanism about the roles of frenolicin B in the growth and development of F. graminearum, an RNA-seq analysis was performed in the mycelia of F. graminearum PH-1 with/without frenolicin B supplementation. In total, 2520 genes, which is ∼21.56% of the total valid genes, were diﬀerentially expressed in frenolicin B treated fungus mycelia in comparison with control mycelia with the criteria of |log2 Fold Change| > 1 and P value <0.05. Of these diﬀerentially expressed genes (DEGs), 1396 genes were upregulated, whereas 1124 genes were downregulated in frenolicin B treated fungus mycelia (Figure S6). To investigate the detailed functions of frenolicin B eﬀects on F. graminearum, the GO terms and KEGG pathways were analyzed on the basis of GSEA. A total of 120 GO terms and 17 KEGG pathways were screened on the basis of P value <0.05 from 833 GO terms and 99 KEGG pathways. Among the top 30 GO terms and all 17 KEGG pathways (sorted by their enrichment score in ascending order; Table 3 and Table S2), the downregulated genes were predominant and there were 16 GO terms and 16 KEGG pathways associated with the metabolism, suggesting that the various metabolic processes in F. graminearum are dramatically suppressed after frenolicin B treatment. P plays an irreplaceable role in the growth of microorganisms by participating in most aspects of energy metabolism, nucleotide and protein synthesis, and kinase regulation.43 Acid phosphatase, alkaline phosphatase, and phytase have high capacities to mineralize organic P or solubilize inorganic P in the environment for microbial utilization.44−46 In contrast, phosphate permease can transport P into the cell under the low-P conditiona.47 These genes enable microorganisms to utilize P eﬃciently and to immobilize P into their biomass.48 Thus, the expressions of these genes were inhibited by frenolicin B, which may impair the metabolism of nucleotides and energy of F. graminearum. In this study, all DEGs associated with glutathione S-transferase (GST) were high expressions (Tables S5 and S6). GSTs are a family of multifunctional enzymes that play a important role in the detoxiﬁcation of both endogenous and xenobiotic compounds, thereby protecting cells against oxidative stress.49 In the top 30 upregulated DEGs, some genes related to oxidoreductase were obviously upregulated (Table S5). Therefore, the activation of GSTs expression level may be used to defend against the reactive oxygen species (ROS) accumulation caused by frenolicin B. A previous study also showed that the ROS level in Fusarium oxysporum was increased by thymol, which led to the signiﬁcant upregulation of GST expression.50

Peroxiredoxin 1 (Prx1) and glutaredoxin 3 (Grx3), two major antioxidant proteins, have been reported to be the eﬀective targets of frenolicin B in tumor cells. The inhibition of Prx1 and Grx3 by frenolicin B resulted in a decrease in cellular glutathione levels and led to an increase in reactive ROS. However, the expression levels of Prx1 (FGSG_03180, log2 Fold Change = 1.11849) and Grx3 (FGSG_02097, log2 Fold Change = 1.89794) in F. graminearum mycelia by frenolicin B treatment were slightly upregulated. This result indicated that frenolicin B may have diﬀerent targets for F. graminearum from tumor cells, and the upregulated expression of the two genes may play a role in the response to oxidative stress.11 Furthermore, myosin-5 gene (FGSG_01410), the speciﬁc target of phenamacril against F. graminearum that had signiﬁcantly upregulated expression by phenamacril treatment, was not found in the DEGs,51 suggesting that the antifungal mechanism of frenolicin B was diﬀerent from that of phenamacril. To conﬁrm the observed changes in gene expression of F. graminearum PH-1 treated by frenolicin B, three key genes that were related to phosphorus metabolism (FGSG_04504, FGSG_07375, FGSG_03172) were further analyzed by qRT- PCR. The result showed that the transcription of the three genes was downregulated to varying degrees after the mycelia were treated with frenolicin B (Figure 5), which was consistent with the RNA-seq analysis.

In conclusion, by means of an activity-guided method, the active compound frenolicin B was isolated and identiﬁed. Frenolicin B exhibited strong antifungal activity against Fusarium species in vitro and showed higher control eﬃcacy in comparison to those of carbendazim and phenamacril on limiting FHB occurrence in ﬁeld trials. Moreover, there was no cross-resistance between frenolicin B and carbendazim on the basis of the in vitro activity test, and the antifungal mechanism of frenolicin B was diﬀerent from phenamacril on the basis of the transcriptome analysis, which suggest that combining or alternating he application of frenolicin B with any of these https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jafc.0c04277 J. As a potential agrochemical fungicide, the relatively low yield of frenolicin B (3.2 mg of frenolicin B per liter of fermentation broth) will hinder its commercial application. Thus, further improvement in the fermentation yield is under way. The preliminary action mechanism investigation indicated that frenolicin B may aﬀect the phosphorus acquisition of F. graminearum and thereby inhibit the metabolism of nucleotides and energy. Further research is needed on the speciﬁc targets exerting antifungal activity.
